Ingredients:500ml (2 cups) self-raising flour10ml (2 tsp) baking powderPinch of salt45ml (3 tbsp) caster sugarFinely grated zest of 1 orange15-30ml (1-2 tbsp) fresh rosemary, finely chopped60ml (4 tbsp) oil160ml buttermilk or plain yoghurt, plus extra if necessary1 extra-large eggExtra milk for glazingLight brown sugar and extra finely grated orange zestMethod: 1) In a large bowl, sift the flour, baking powder, salt and caster sugar together. Add the zest and fresh rosemary. 2) Combine the oil, buttermilk and egg.3) Add the wet ingredients to the dry ingredients and bring the dough together, adding extra buttermilk if necessary. 4) On a lightly floured surface, pat out the scone mixture so it s about 3-4cm thick. Use a fluted 6cm cutter to cut out scones and place on a baking tray sprayed with cooking spray. Don't have a cutter? Gently press the dough into a 20cm cake pan using a sharp knife to mark out wedges.5) Brush with milk and sprinkle over brown sugar and orange zest. Allow to stand for 10 minutes. Leave to stand for 10 minutes; this activates the baking powder resulting in lighter, fluffier scones.6) Bake at 200 C for 15 minutes.</img>Cheese and chive scones. Top tip: for light and fluffy scones, don t use a rolling pin. Rather press out the dough on a lightly floured surface before cutting out. Image: iStock Cheese and chive scones. Top tip: for light and fluffy scones, don t use a rolling pin. Rather press out the dough on a lightly floured surface before cutting out. Image: iStock Ingredients:500ml (2 cups) self-raising flour10ml (2 tsp) baking powderLarge pinch of saltGenerous sprinkle of cayenne pepper250ml (1 cup) strong cheddar cheese, gratedSmall handful of chives or parsley, finely chopped60ml (4 tbsp) oil160ml buttermilk or plain yoghurt, plus extra if necessary1 extra-large egg plus an extra one for glazing5ml (1tsp) readymade mustardSesame seeds, optionalHow to make feather-light buttermilk sconesMethod:1) In a large bowl, sift the flour, baking powder, salt and cayenne pepper. Add the cheese and chives and mix through the flour. 2) Beat the oil, buttermilk, egg and mustard together. 3) Make a well in the centre of the dry ingredients and mix through the egg and buttermilk mixture, adding extra buttermilk if needed. Mix together gently without over-handling.4) On a lightly floured surface, pat out the scone mixture so it s about 3-4cm thick. Use a fluted 6cm cutter to cut out scones and place on a baking tray sprayed with cooking spray. Don't have a cutter? Gently press the dough into a 20cm cake pan using a sharp knife to mark out wedges.5) Brush with egg and sprinkle with sesame seeds. Leave to stand for 10 minutes; this activates the baking powder resulting in lighter, fluffier scones.6) at 200 C for 12-15 minutes.